# Implementation Plan: OSSA Org Proxy & UI Enhancements

## 1. Overview
The goal is to separate concerns by moving the heavy CLI processing out of `openstandardagents.org` and into `openstandard-ui` (which will be hosted on `ossa-ui.blueflyagents.com`). The `.org` website will act as a thin client proxying to the new UI platform, while adhering to decentralized agent discovery and platform UI standards.

## 2. Execution Phase

### Step 2.1: Implement API Logic in `openstandard-ui`
- **Location:** `openstandard-ui/app/api/manifest/generate/route.ts` (and an export route).
- **Task:** Port the existing `child_process.execFile` logic currently sitting in [openstandardagents.org/website/app/api/agent-builder/route.ts](file:///Users/flux423/Sites/blueflyio/WORKING_DEMOs/openstandardagents.org/website/app/api/agent-builder/route.ts).
- **Details:** The new route must accept the payload (manifest YAML, platform targets, agent name) and run `ossa init`, `validate`, and `export` using `@bluefly/openstandardagents` CLI, returning the generated files and logs as a unified JSON response.

### Step 2.2: Standardize Builder UI Components
- **Location:** `openstandard-ui`
- **Task:** Audit and update the UI layers for the builder to ensure it correctly and cleanly consumes the platform standard UI library (`studio-ui`). This avoids duplicate UI implementations.

### Step 2.3: Integrate Decentralized Agent Discovery (UADP)
- **Location:** `ossa-ui` API endpoints (and `.org` playground rendering components).
- **Task:** Introduce decentralized discovery logic so the platform can query and list available agents dynamically.
- **Details:** Read from local/remote sources like `.agents-workspace` or `agent-mesh` repositories seamlessly. The `.org` site’s interactive playground (e.g., `<InteractivePlayground />`) will consume this endpoint to render actual discovered agents dynamically instead of hardcoded examples.

### Step 2.4: Convert `.org` API to Proxy Endpoint
- **Location:** [openstandardagents.org/website/app/api/agent-builder/route.ts](file:///Users/flux423/Sites/blueflyio/WORKING_DEMOs/openstandardagents.org/website/app/api/agent-builder/route.ts)
- **Task:** Gut the local `execFile` execution.
- **Details:** Refactor the GET and POST handlers to securely proxy requests to `https://ossa-ui.blueflyagents.com/api/...` passing through any req body and forwarding the response back to the local React frontend.

### Step 2.5: Route Frontend Links and UI Connectors
- **Location:** [openstandardagents.org/website/app/page.tsx](file:///Users/flux423/Sites/blueflyio/WORKING_DEMOs/openstandardagents.org/website/app/page.tsx) and builder UI components.
- **Task:** Maintain the frontend builder experience on `.org`, but ensure calls map properly to the proxy. We will also update "Try now" / "Get started" external entry points where applicable to link directly to the new `ossa-ui.blueflyagents.com` platform.

## 3. Deployment Phase (Oracle Migration Prep)
Once the code merges, we will draft an Oracle deployment checklist covering:
1. Environment Vars configuration (`OSSA_UI_EXTERNAL_URI` etc.) pointing to `ossa-ui.blueflyagents.com`.
2. Re-verifying Node.js proxy runtimes avoiding OS level shell dependencies (since Next.js will no longer execute the CLI locally, removing Docker/worktree constraints).
3. Routing, container definitions, and CI updates needed for launching the thin `.org` wrapper onto Oracle infrastructure.

## 4. NIST CAISI Alignment & Stabilization (New Phases)

### Phase 1: Stabilization & Security Hardening (Current)
- Refactor `openstandard-ui`'s `/api/agent-builder` to use the OSSA CLI programmatically instead of `child_process.execFile` against a temporary file system, ensuring pure in-memory compilation.
- Implement robust Zod validation on incoming manifest payloads.
- Update `openstandardagents.org` site to explicitly feature a "NIST CAISI Alignment" section to capitalize on the February 2026 AI Agent Standards Initiative announcement.

### Phase 2: NIST Identity Alignment
- Introduce an `x-signature` block to `ossa.yaml` for cryptographic provenance.
- Wire `TrustBadge` UI to perform actual DID/PKI verification against agent signatures.
- Draft formal response to the NIST RFI on Agent Identity and Authorization.

### Phase 3: Decentralized Protocol Robustness
- Formalize the Universal Agent Discovery Protocol (UADP) into an explicitly documented OpenAPI/AsyncAPI specification.
